Custom rate limiter — when you write your own class
You'd do this if you want logic beyond what RequestRateLimiter supports (e.g., your own Lua script with different semantics, per-tier limits pulled from a DB, sliding window instead of token bucket).
Step 1 — extend AbstractGatewayFilterFactory:
java@Component
public class CustomRateLimiterGatewayFilterFactory
        extends AbstractGatewayFilterFactory<CustomRateLimiterGatewayFilterFactory.Config> {

    private final ReactiveStringRedisTemplate redisTemplate;

    public CustomRateLimiterGatewayFilterFactory(ReactiveStringRedisTemplate redisTemplate) {
        super(Config.class);
        this.redisTemplate = redisTemplate;
    }

    @Override
    public GatewayFilter apply(Config config) {
        return (exchange, chain) -> {
            String key = "rate_limit:" + exchange.getRequest().getRemoteAddress();

            return checkTokenBucket(key, config.getCapacity(), config.getRefillRate())
                .flatMap(allowed -> {
                    if (allowed) {
                        return chain.filter(exchange);
                    } else {
                        exchange.getResponse().setStatusCode(HttpStatus.TOO_MANY_REQUESTS);
                        return exchange.getResponse().setComplete();
                    }
                });
        };
    }

    private Mono<Boolean> checkTokenBucket(String key, int capacity, int refillRate) {
        // your Lua script execution goes here
        return Mono.just(true); // placeholder
    }

    public static class Config {
        private int capacity;
        private int refillRate;
        // getters/setters
    }
}
Step 2 — the class name convention:
Class must be named <Something>GatewayFilterFactory. Spring strips GatewayFilterFactory off the end and that remainder is what you reference in YAML:
yamlfilters:
  - name: CustomRateLimiter    # matches CustomRateLimiterGatewayFilterFactory
    args:
      capacity: 20
      refillRate: 10
Step 3 — args: mapping:
The Config inner class fields (capacity, refillRate) get bound automatically from the YAML args: map by field name — Spring uses reflection/data-binding, same mechanism as @ConfigurationProperties. No manual parsing needed.


java// Old style (blocking) — like standing at the counter
String value = redisTemplate.get("key");  // your thread FREEZES here until Redis replies
System.out.println(value);
java// Reactive style — like the buzzer
Mono<String> value = redisTemplate.get("key");  // NOTHING has happened yet. Just a buzzer.

value.subscribe(v -> System.out.println(v));
// ONLY NOW does Redis actually get called.
// And when it replies, THIS specific line of code (the println) runs.